\f1\fs24 \cf2 Set this project up to run locally in emulator mode only.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 Requirements:\cb1 \
\cb3 - Use Node 20, not Node 24/25\cb1 \
\cb3 - Use Java 21\cb1 \
\cb3 - Do not use live Firebase\cb1 \
\cb3 - Do not deploy anything\cb1 \
\cb3 - Do not ask for firebase login unless absolutely necessary\cb1 \
\cb3 - Repo root already uses emulator mode by default\cb1 \
\
\cb3 Steps:\cb1 \
\cb3 1. Verify node -v, npm -v, and java -version\cb1 \
\cb3 2. Ensure the repo is not inside OneDrive/Desktop/Documents on Windows\cb1 \
\cb3 3. Run:\cb1 \
\cb3    npm ci\cb1 \
\cb3    npm --prefix functions ci\cb1 \
\cb3 4. Create functions/.secret.local with:\cb1 \
\cb3    GEMINI_API_KEY=YOUR_GEMINI_KEY_HERE\cb1 \
\cb3 5. Start terminal 1 with:\cb1 \
\cb3    npx firebase emulators:start --only auth,functions,firestore,storage\cb1 \
\cb3 6. Wait until the output says "All emulators ready"\cb1 \
\cb3 7. Start terminal 2 with:\cb1 \
\cb3    npm run dev -- --port 5173 --strictPort\cb1 \
\cb3 8. Report the final URLs:\cb1 \
\cb3    http://localhost:5173\cb1 \
\cb3    http://127.0.0.1:4000\cb1 \
\cb3 9. If npm ci fails on Windows with EPERM, kill node/java processes, delete node_modules and functions/node_modules, and retry.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

